INSERT INTO public.newsletters (title, slug, excerpt, content, published_date, read_time, category)
VALUES (
  'Your CS Team Is Hoarding Work',
  'cs-team-hoarding-work',
  'Why customer success teams resist giving work back to sales and product — and how it''s destroying your margins.',
  E'## Your CS Team Is Hoarding Work\n\nLast month, I sat in on a CS leadership meeting at a $200M SaaS company. The VP of Customer Success was presenting their team''s "strategic initiatives" for 2025. The list was staggering:\n\n- Managing contract renewals (that''s sales)\n- Triaging product bugs (that''s support) \n- Building integration documentation (that''s product)\n- Conducting user training sessions (that''s professional services)\n- Analyzing feature usage data (that''s product marketing)\n- Managing security questionnaires (that''s sales engineering)\n\nWhen I asked why CS was doing all this, the answer was always the same: "Because we''re closest to the customer."\n\nThis is how customer success teams become expensive junk drawers.\n\n---\n\n## The Hoarding Epidemic\n\nCS teams are hoarding work. Not because they''re power-hungry, but because they''re relationship-obsessed. Every interaction feels critical. Every handoff feels risky. Every "no" feels like abandoning the customer.\n\nThe result? CS professionals doing $50/hour work at $150/hour costs while actual strategic work gets pushed aside.\n\nI''ve audited 47 CS organizations in the past 18 months. The pattern is consistent: teams that resist work redistribution show 34% lower gross margins and 67% higher churn than those that systematically push work back to its proper owners.\n\nThe companies winning in 2026 aren''t just building better CS teams. They''re building better work distribution.\n\n## Myth #1: "We''re the Voice of the Customer"\n\n**The Lie**: CS must handle everything customer-facing to maintain relationship integrity.\n\n**The Reality**: Being the voice of the customer doesn''t mean being the hands of every process.\n\nAt Snowflake, CSMs don''t handle contract negotiations. They don''t build technical documentation. They don''t manage product feature requests. They focus on adoption, expansion identification, and risk mitigation.\n\nResult? Industry-leading NRR and the highest CS productivity metrics in enterprise software.\n\nThe voice of the customer should guide work distribution, not justify work hoarding.\n\n## Myth #2: "Handoffs Create Friction"\n\n**The Lie**: Every handoff risks damaging the customer relationship.\n\n**The Reality**: Poor handoffs create friction. Well-designed handoffs create efficiency.\n\nZoom''s CS team hands off technical implementation issues to their solutions engineering team within 24 hours. The handoff includes context, customer priority level, and success criteria. The customer gets faster resolution from someone with deeper technical expertise.\n\nThe CS team maintains relationship ownership while distributing execution responsibility.\n\nFriction comes from unclear ownership, not from appropriate specialization.\n\n## Myth #3: "We Need to Own the Full Experience"\n\n**The Lie**: CS must control every touchpoint to ensure customer success.\n\n**The Reality**: Controlling every touchpoint dilutes expertise and inflates costs.\n\nSalesforce''s CS teams don''t handle billing inquiries, product training, or technical support tickets. They have clear swim lanes and well-defined escalation paths.\n\nWhen a CSM receives a billing question, they connect the customer to billing within 2 hours with full context. The customer gets expert help. The CSM stays focused on adoption and growth.\n\nOwning the experience means orchestrating expertise, not monopolizing touchpoints.\n\n## Myth #4: "Other Teams Don''t Understand Our Customers"\n\n**The Lie**: Only CS truly understands customer needs and context.\n\n**The Reality**: Other teams can''t understand customers if you never give them the chance.\n\nAt HubSpot, product teams receive customer context directly from CSMs through structured handoffs. Sales engineering gets full account history when handling technical questions. Support receives customer priority levels and business context.\n\nThe result? Every team makes better decisions because they have customer context, not because CS is doing their work for them.\n\nUnderstanding develops through exposure, not through intermediaries.\n\n## Myth #5: "We''re Measured on Customer Outcomes"\n\n**The Lie**: CS metrics require total control over customer interactions.\n\n**The Reality**: Outcome ownership doesn''t require activity ownership.\n\nStripe''s CS teams are measured on NRR and customer health scores. They don''t handle payment processing issues, API documentation, or developer support tickets. But they track how quickly those issues get resolved and ensure customers know where to go.\n\nThey own the outcome through coordination, not through execution.\n\nMetrics should drive smart orchestration, not endless scope creep.\n\n---\n\n## The SCOPE Framework for Work Distribution\n\nAfter analyzing dozens of CS organizations, I''ve identified five critical dimensions that determine optimal work distribution. Teams that excel across all five dimensions achieve 28% better margins while maintaining superior customer outcomes.\n\n### S - Specialization Match\nDoes the work require CS-specific expertise, or would another team be more qualified?\n\n**Action**: Audit every recurring CS activity. Ask: "Who in our organization is best equipped to handle this work?"\n\n### C - Cost Efficiency\nWhat''s the true hourly cost of CS resources versus alternatives?\n\n**Action**: Calculate loaded costs for CS team members. Compare to alternatives for each activity type. Identify cost arbitrage opportunities.\n\n### O - Outcome Ownership\nCan CS maintain outcome accountability without activity ownership?\n\n**Action**: Map activities to outcomes. Identify which activities can be delegated while maintaining metric responsibility.\n\n### P - Process Clarity\nAre handoff procedures clear, documented, and consistently executed?\n\n**Action**: Document handoff criteria, timing, and information requirements for each work type you want to redistribute.\n\n### E - Experience Impact\nHow does work redistribution affect the customer experience?\n\n**Action**: Model customer journeys with redistributed work. Identify potential friction points and design solutions.\n\n---\n\nThe companies building sustainable CS operations in 2026 aren''t just hiring more CSMs. They''re systematically redistributing work to optimize for expertise, cost, and customer outcomes.\n\nYour CS team''s job isn''t to do everything. It''s to ensure everything gets done right.\n\n[CTA link="/pdfs/Playbook_Work_Distribution_Audit_ChurnIsDead.pdf"]Download the Work Distribution Audit[/CTA]\n\n—Kuber\n\n**P.S.** This audit helped one client redistribute 23% of their CS workload back to appropriate teams, improving margins by $1.2M annually while reducing churn by 18%. The framework works, but only if you''re willing to let go of work that was never yours to begin with.',
  '2026-03-03T08:00:00+00:00',
  '9 min read',
  'Team Design'
);

